const crypto = require('crypto');
function id(q) { return 'card-' + crypto.createHash('sha256').update(q.trim().toLowerCase()).digest('hex').slice(0,12); }
const cards = [];
function add(topicId, question, answer, explanation, difficulty, bloomLevel, tags) {
  cards.push({ id: id(question), question, answer, explanation, difficulty, bloomLevel, tags, topicId });
}

// EMERGENCY MEDICINE - em-tox (15)
add('em-tox','A 22-year-old presents after intentional overdose of unknown pills. GCS 13, miosis, RR 8, oxygen saturation 88%. What is the toxidrome and treatment?','Opioid toxidrome (miosis, respiratory depression, altered consciousness); administer naloxone 0.4-2 mg IV/IM/intranasal, support airway with BVM, titrate to adequate respiration (not full reversal)','ACEP/CAEP toxicology guidelines: opioid toxidrome is life-threatening primarily through respiratory depression. Naloxone is short-acting — monitor for re-narcotization (especially with long-acting opioids or fentanyl). May need naloxone infusion. Poison Control Centre: 1-800-268-9017 (Ontario) or regional numbers.',4,'apply',['opioid overdose','naloxone','toxidrome','respiratory depression','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','What are the key toxidromes and their distinguishing features?','Opioid: miosis, bradypnea, sedation; Sympathomimetic: mydriasis, tachycardia, hyperthermia, diaphoresis; Anticholinergic: mydriasis, dry skin, hyperthermia, urinary retention, ileus, confusion (mad as hatter, hot as hare, dry as bone, blind as bat, red as beet); Cholinergic: SLUDGE/DUMBELS; Serotonin: clonus, hyperreflexia, hyperthermia, agitation','ACLS toxicology: matching clinical features to toxidrome guides antidote selection and management. Anticholinergic toxidrome (antihistamines, TCAs, atropine) treated with physostigmine for severe cases. Cholinergic (organophosphate): atropine + pralidoxime. Serotonin syndrome: cyproheptadine + benzodiazepines.',3,'recall',['toxidromes','anticholinergic','sympathomimetic','cholinergic','serotonin syndrome','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','A patient with acetaminophen overdose presents 4 hours after ingestion. Serum acetaminophen level is 250 mg/L. What is the management?','Plot level on Rumack-Matthew nomogram; if above treatment line: N-acetylcysteine (NAC) IV or oral; if within 4 hours: activated charcoal 1 g/kg (if patient cooperative)','NAC replenishes glutathione, preventing toxic NAPQI from causing hepatotoxicity. Most effective if started within 8 hours. IV NAC: 150 mg/kg over 1h, then 50 mg/kg over 4h, then 100 mg/kg over 16h (21h regimen) — anaphylactoid reactions in 15-20% (managed by slowing infusion, diphenhydramine).',4,'apply',['acetaminophen overdose','NAC','Rumack-Matthew','N-acetylcysteine','toxicology','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','A patient on TCAs (tricyclic antidepressants) presents with hypotension, QRS >120 ms, and seizures. What is the first-line antidote?','Sodium bicarbonate 1-2 mEq/kg IV bolus for QRS >100 ms or hemodynamic instability from TCA toxicity','TCA toxicity causes sodium channel blockade (wide QRS), alpha blockade (hypotension), and antimuscarinic effects. Sodium bicarbonate (target serum pH 7.45-7.55) reverses sodium channel blockade. Avoid physostigmine (can worsen conduction) and flumazenil (lowers seizure threshold). Intralipid for refractory TCA toxicity.',4,'apply',['TCA toxicity','sodium bicarbonate','QRS widening','sodium channel','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','What are the features of serotonin syndrome and how does it differ from NMS?','Serotonin syndrome: ACUTE onset, hyperreflexia, clonus (especially in lower limbs), hyperthermia, agitation, diarrhea — caused by excess serotonergic stimulation; NMS: GRADUAL onset over days, lead-pipe rigidity, no clonus, no diarrhea','Serotonin syndrome causes: SS + MAOI, two serotonergic agents (SSRI + tramadol, SSRI + triptans, SSRI + fentanyl). Treatment: remove precipitating agent, benzodiazepines for agitation/hyperthermia, cyproheptadine (serotonin antagonist) for moderate-severe cases, active cooling.',4,'analyze',['serotonin syndrome','NMS','toxicology','cyproheptadine','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','What is the management of digoxin toxicity?','Digoxin toxicity: nausea, visual changes (yellow-green halos), bradycardia, AV block, hyperkalemia; antidote: digoxin-specific antibody fragments (DigiFab); dose: 10 vials (acute), calculate based on serum level for chronic','Digoxin toxicity triggers: renal failure, hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia, drug interactions (amiodarone, verapamil, macrolides). Hypokalemia potentiates digoxin toxicity. Avoid calcium gluconate in digoxin toxicity (may worsen cardiac effects). DigiFab reverses toxicity within 30 minutes.',4,'apply',['digoxin toxicity','DigiFab','AV block','hyperkalemia','toxicology','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','How is organophosphate (pesticide) poisoning treated?','Large doses of atropine (1-4 mg IV q5-10 min until bronchospasm resolves and secretions dry) + pralidoxime (2-PAM) 1-2 g IV (within 24-48h — reactivates acetylcholinesterase); decontaminate skin, protect rescuers','Organophosphate poisoning: cholinergic toxidrome (SLUDGE: Salivation, Lacrimation, Urination, Defecation, GI distress, Emesis) + CNS effects (seizures). Pralidoxime works best if given early before enzyme aging. Benzodiazepines for seizures. Atropine (not glycopyrrolate) penetrates CNS for CNS effects.',4,'apply',['organophosphate','cholinergic','atropine','pralidoxime','SLUDGE','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','What is the antidote for benzodiazepine overdose and when should it be used?','Flumazenil (Romazicon) is the antidote but rarely used — can precipitate seizures (in chronic BZD users or mixed TCA/BZD overdose), and has short half-life (re-sedation common); reserved for procedural sedation reversal','CAEP toxicology: flumazenil is generally NOT recommended for benzodiazepine overdose in the ED due to seizure risk, especially in patients with chronic BZD dependence or suspected co-ingestion with TCA or other proconvulsants. Supportive care (airway management) is preferred.',4,'analyze',['flumazenil','benzodiazepine overdose','seizure risk','toxicology','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','A patient has methanol poisoning. What are the clinical features and treatment?','Methanol: latent period 12-24h, then anion gap metabolic acidosis, visual disturbances (snowfield vision), fundoscopy shows optic disc hyperemia; treat with fomepizole (preferred) or ethanol to block alcohol dehydrogenase; hemodialysis for severe toxicity','Methanol → formaldehyde → formic acid (causes optic nerve toxicity and metabolic acidosis). Fomepizole (4-MP) blocks alcohol dehydrogenase without sedation. Folinic acid enhances formate elimination. Hemodialysis if: pH <7.15, visual symptoms, serum methanol >15 mmol/L.',4,'apply',['methanol poisoning','fomepizole','anion gap metabolic acidosis','visual disturbance','toxicology','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','What is the treatment for iron overdose?','Iron overdose: abdominal pain, vomiting (may have bloody), anion gap metabolic acidosis (Phases I-IV); antidote: deferoxamine IV (chelates free iron) for: symptomatic toxicity, serum iron >90 μmol/L, anion gap acidosis','Iron toxicity phase: I (0-6h: GI symptoms), II (6-24h: apparent improvement), III (12-48h: systemic toxicity — shock, acidosis), IV (2-5 days: hepatic failure), V (chronic: GI scarring). Deferoxamine chelates iron → ferrioxamine → excreted in urine (vin rosé urine color).',4,'apply',['iron overdose','deferoxamine','iron toxicity','antidote','toxicology','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','What is the management of cyanide poisoning?','Cyanide poisoning (house fires with synthetic materials, nitroprusside toxicity): hydroxocobalamin (Cyanokit) 5g IV is antidote — also sodium nitrite + sodium thiosulfate as alternative','Cyanide inhibits cytochrome c oxidase → cellular hypoxia → lactic acidosis. Signs: high anion gap metabolic acidosis, cherry red skin (classic), normal PaO2 despite profound toxicity. Hydroxocobalamin chelates cyanide to form cyanocobalamin. 100% O2 to increase O2 delivery.',4,'apply',['cyanide poisoning','hydroxocobalamin','house fire','metabolic acidosis','toxicology','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','What is the role of activated charcoal in overdose management?','Activated charcoal 1 g/kg (max 50g) within 1-2 hours of ingestion for most oral overdoses (exceptions: iron, lithium, alcohols, hydrocarbons, caustics — not adsorbed by charcoal); risk: aspiration if airway not protected','ACEP toxicology: activated charcoal is most effective within 1 hour. After 2 hours, benefit is much less. Contraindications: unprotected airway, caustic ingestion, ileus, bowel obstruction. Multi-dose activated charcoal for salicylates, carbamazepine, phenobarbital, theophylline.',3,'apply',['activated charcoal','overdose decontamination','aspiration risk','toxicology','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','A patient has severe metabolic acidosis and high anion gap after ingestion of antifreeze. What is the diagnosis and management?','Ethylene glycol poisoning; antidote: fomepizole 15 mg/kg IV bolus (preferred) or ethanol; aggressive IV hydration; hemodialysis for: pH <7.3, renal failure, serum ethylene glycol >8 mmol/L','Ethylene glycol → glycolic acid → oxalic acid → calcium oxalate crystals (damage renal tubules). Urine: oxalate crystals (monohydrate and dihydrate), Woods lamp fluorescence if fluorescein in antifreeze. Aggressive treatment to prevent permanent renal failure.',4,'apply',['ethylene glycol','antifreeze','fomepizole','metabolic acidosis','toxicology','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','What are the features and management of local anesthetic systemic toxicity (LAST)?','LAST: CNS (metallic taste, perioral tingling, seizures, coma) and cardiovascular toxicity (arrhythmias, cardiac arrest); treat with 20% lipid emulsion (Intralipid 1.5 mL/kg IV bolus) + CPR if arrest','Lipid rescue (Intralipid) is the specific antidote for LAST — sequesters lipophilic local anesthetic in lipid sink. Prevention: aspirate before injection, slow injection rate, use lowest effective dose. Bupivacaine is the most cardiotoxic local anesthetic. Max dose epinephrine-containing lidocaine: 7 mg/kg.',4,'apply',['LAST','local anesthetic toxicity','Intralipid','lipid rescue','toxicology','emergency medicine']);
add('em-tox','What is the GHB (gamma-hydroxybutyrate) toxidrome and management?','GHB: date rape drug; CNS and respiratory depression mimicking opioids, but NOT reversed by naloxone; management: supportive (airway, O2), short-duration (1-4h); agitation: benzodiazepines','GHB has a very steep dose-response curve — small dose increase causes sudden profound coma. Patients may appear deeply unconscious then wake up abruptly. Distinguish from opioids (naloxone ineffective) and alcohol (shorter duration). GHB withdrawal (chronic users): similar to alcohol/benzodiazepine withdrawal.',3,'apply',['GHB','date rape drug','CNS depression','toxidrome','emergency medicine']);

// EMERGENCY MEDICINE - em-anaphylaxis (10)
add('em-anaphylaxis','A 28-year-old develops generalized urticaria, laryngeal edema, wheezing, and hypotension 10 minutes after a bee sting. Diagnosis and immediate management?','Anaphylaxis; immediate IM epinephrine 0.3-0.5 mg (1:1000 solution) in outer thigh — this is the FIRST priority, not antihistamines or steroids','CAEP/WAO anaphylaxis guidelines: epinephrine is the only life-saving medication. Delay in epinephrine is associated with deaths. Antihistamines and steroids are adjuncts only (no effect on anaphylaxis course). 30-minute observation for uniphasic reactions; 4-6h for those requiring epinephrine. Prescribe epinephrine auto-injector at discharge.',5,'analyze',['anaphylaxis','epinephrine','epi-pen','anaphylactic shock','emergency medicine']);
add('em-anaphylaxis','What is the Sampson criteria for diagnosing anaphylaxis?','Anaphylaxis when any one of: (1) Acute onset illness with skin/mucosal involvement + respiratory compromise or hypotension; (2) ≥2 symptoms after allergen exposure (skin, respiratory, GI, hypotension); (3) Hypotension after known allergen exposure','WAO/CAEP criteria identify 95% of anaphylaxis cases. Skin/mucosal involvement absent in ~20% of severe anaphylaxis — do not rely on urticaria for diagnosis. Monitor for biphasic reactions (recurrence 4-8h later without re-exposure, occurring in 5-20%).',3,'recall',['anaphylaxis criteria','Sampson criteria','biphasic anaphylaxis','diagnosis','emergency medicine']);
add('em-anaphylaxis','What is the dosing of IM epinephrine for anaphylaxis and why is the IM route preferred over IV?','IM: 0.3-0.5 mg of 1:1000 epinephrine in outer thigh; IM preferred over SQ (more reliable absorption); IV epinephrine only for cardiac arrest or severe refractory anaphylaxis (risk of severe arrhythmias at IM doses)','Outer thigh IM injection results in faster absorption and higher peak levels than upper arm IM or SC. IV epinephrine for anaphylaxis requires careful dose reduction and dilution (1:10,000 or 1:100,000 solution) — errors are fatal. Repeat IM epinephrine q5-15 min if needed.',3,'apply',['epinephrine dosing','anaphylaxis','IM injection','outer thigh','emergency medicine']);
add('em-anaphylaxis','What are the triggers for anaphylaxis in Canada and which is the most common trigger in adults?','Foods (most common overall: peanuts, tree nuts, shellfish, fish, milk, eggs, wheat); Medications (most common in adults — especially penicillin, NSAIDs, contrast media); Insect stings (bees, wasps); Latex; Exercise; Idiopathic','CAEP guidelines: food is the most common trigger in children; medications are most common in adults and elderly. Latex allergy is common in healthcare workers. Idiopathic anaphylaxis is a diagnosis of exclusion. Alpha-tryptase levels (1-2h after reaction) confirm mast cell activation.',2,'recall',['anaphylaxis triggers','food allergy','drug allergy','insect sting','emergency medicine']);
add('em-anaphylaxis','What are the adjunct medications used in anaphylaxis management (after epinephrine)?','IV H1 antihistamine (diphenhydramine 25-50mg), IV H2 antihistamine (ranitidine 50mg), IV corticosteroids (hydrocortisone 200mg or methylprednisolone 125mg), bronchodilator (salbutamol) for wheeze, IV fluids for hypotension','CAEP guidelines: these adjuncts do NOT replace epinephrine. Antihistamines address urticaria/itching but do NOT prevent or treat respiratory compromise or hypotension. Corticosteroids may prevent biphasic reactions (limited evidence). All patients should receive epinephrine first.',2,'recall',['anaphylaxis management','diphenhydramine','corticosteroids','adjuncts','emergency medicine']);
add('em-anaphylaxis','What is biphasic anaphylaxis and who is at risk?','Biphasic anaphylaxis: recurrence of symptoms 1-72 hours (typically 4-8h) after initial resolution without further allergen exposure; occurs in 5-20% of cases; risk factors: severe initial reaction, unknown trigger, delayed epinephrine treatment','CAEP guidelines: biphasic reactions are unpredictable. Observation for 4-6 hours after epinephrine administration. Some guidelines recommend 24-hour observation for severe reactions or those with unknown triggers. Discharge criteria: hemodynamically stable, symptoms resolved, discharge with epinephrine auto-injector.',4,'analyze',['biphasic anaphylaxis','observation period','recurrence','emergency medicine']);
add('em-anaphylaxis','A patient has suspected anaphylaxis to penicillin and requires urgent surgery. Is cephalosporin safe to use?','Cross-reactivity between penicillin and cephalosporins is ~1-2% (not 10% as previously thought); use with caution based on specific allergy history — desensitization protocol if penicillin is essential for surgical infection prophylaxis','Allergy Canada and CAEP guidelines: 90% of patients with self-reported penicillin allergy tolerate penicillin and cephalosporins. True immediate hypersensitivity mediated by IgE. Cross-reactivity based on R1 side chain similarity — 1st generation cephalosporins have higher cross-reactivity. Skin testing for penicillin allergy is gold standard.',4,'analyze',['penicillin allergy','cephalosporin cross-reactivity','drug allergy','desensitization','emergency medicine']);
add('em-anaphylaxis','What are the discharge instructions for a patient treated for anaphylaxis?','Prescribe epinephrine auto-injector x2 (EpiPen), allergist referral, medical alert bracelet, written action plan, antihistamines and corticosteroids for mild reactions (NOT in place of epinephrine), return if symptoms recur, food/drug avoidance counseling','CAEP anaphylaxis guidelines: all patients discharged after anaphylaxis require epinephrine auto-injector prescription and training on use. Referral to allergist for allergen identification and immunotherapy (desensitization for bee venom, penicillin). Patients on beta-blockers: epinephrine may be less effective.',3,'apply',['anaphylaxis discharge','EpiPen','allergist referral','action plan','emergency medicine']);
add('em-anaphylaxis','What medications can interfere with the treatment of anaphylaxis?','Beta-blockers: blunt epinephrine effect (can cause severe hypertension via unopposed alpha-agonism), may require IV glucagon 1-2 mg; ACE inhibitors: increase bradykinin, worsen angioedema and hypotension','CAEP guidelines: patients on beta-blockers who develop anaphylaxis require higher epinephrine doses and/or IV glucagon (reverses beta-blockade). ACE inhibitor-induced angioedema: hereditary angioedema treatment (icatibant/ecallantide) may be needed. Pre-existing mast cell disease (mastocytosis) worsens anaphylaxis severity.',3,'apply',['beta-blockers anaphylaxis','glucagon','ACE inhibitor angioedema','anaphylaxis management','emergency medicine']);
add('em-anaphylaxis','What is hereditary angioedema (HAE) and how is it differentiated from anaphylactic angioedema?','HAE: C1 inhibitor deficiency causing recurrent angioedema without urticaria, triggered by stress/trauma/estrogens — NOT responsive to epinephrine, antihistamines, or steroids; treat with C1-INH concentrate, icatibant, or ecallantide','HAE Type I (85%): low C1-INH level and function; Type II (15%): normal level, reduced function; Type III: estrogen-sensitive, normal C1-INH. Laboratory: low C4 (consumed even between attacks), low C1-INH level/function. Laryngeal involvement can cause death. Prophylaxis: tranexamic acid, attenuated androgens, C1-INH concentrate.',4,'analyze',['hereditary angioedema','HAE','C1 inhibitor','icatibant','angioedema','emergency medicine']);

// PUBLIC HEALTH - ph-screening (15)
add('ph-screening','What is the Canadian Task Force on Preventive Health Care (CTFPHC) recommendation for colorectal cancer screening?','Fecal immunochemical test (FIT) every 2 years for adults aged 50-74; flexible sigmoidoscopy every 10 years as alternative; colonoscopy for average-risk as screening (not endorsed by CTFPHC but provincial guidelines vary)','CTFPHC CRC screening guidelines: FIT is non-invasive, cost-effective, and achieves high adherence. Positive FIT requires follow-up colonoscopy. High-risk individuals (IBD, family history, hereditary syndrome) require direct colonoscopy as per CAG/CCA guidelines.',2,'recall',['colorectal cancer screening','FIT','CTFPHC','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What is the CTFPHC recommendation for breast cancer screening by age group?','Women 50-74: routine screening mammography every 2-3 years (strong recommendation); Women 40-49: recommend against routine screening (moderate recommendation — number needed to screen vs. harms); Women 75+: insufficient evidence','CTFPHC 2018 breast cancer guidelines: benefits of mammography (mortality reduction) must be weighed against harms (false positives, overdiagnosis, unnecessary biopsies). High-risk women (BRCA, family history): annual MRI + mammogram starting at 30-40 per Cancer Care Ontario/BC Cancer.',2,'recall',['breast cancer screening','mammography','CTFPHC','50-74','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What is the recommended cervical cancer screening strategy in Canada?','Pap test (liquid-based cytology) every 3 years for women 21-69; HPV primary testing every 5 years increasingly adopted provincially — stop after age 69 with adequate prior screening or after total hysterectomy for benign indication','CTFPHC and SOGC cervical cancer screening guidelines: HPV primary testing has higher sensitivity than cytology. Several provinces are transitioning to HPV testing with cytology reflex. Women with abnormal results require colposcopy per provincial algorithms. Pap testing begins at age 21 (not at first sexual activity as previously).',2,'recall',['cervical cancer screening','Pap test','HPV testing','CTFPHC','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What are the Canadian guidelines for lung cancer screening?','Low-dose CT (LDCT) screening annually for high-risk individuals: age 50-74 years, smoking history ≥20 pack-years, current smoker OR quit within 15 years — Cancer Care Ontario/BC Cancer recommendations (CTFPHC recommends for 50-74 with ≥20 pack-years)','NLST and NELSON trials showed LDCT reduces lung cancer mortality by 20-25% in high-risk populations. Harms: false positives (20-25% of screens), unnecessary procedures, radiation exposure. Smoking cessation counseling must accompany lung cancer screening programs. Pan-Canadian LDCT implementation is ongoing.',3,'apply',['lung cancer screening','LDCT','CTFPHC','smoking','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What is the CTFPHC recommendation for prostate cancer screening with PSA?','CTFPHC recommends AGAINST routine PSA screening for average-risk men due to overdiagnosis and treatment harms — individualized decision-making for men 55-69 after full informed discussion of benefits and harms','PSA screening: reduces prostate cancer mortality by ~20% but leads to significant overdiagnosis and overtreatment (incontinence, sexual dysfunction from treatment of cancers that may never cause symptoms). CTFPHC weak recommendation against; Cancer Care Ontario: individualized decision-making for 50-70 years.',3,'recall',['PSA screening','prostate cancer','CTFPHC','overdiagnosis','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What is the recommended screening approach for abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) in Canada?','One-time ultrasound screening for men aged 65-80 years who have ever smoked (≥100 cigarettes lifetime) — CTFPHC recommendation; AAA: ≥3 cm; repair if ≥5.5 cm or rapid growth','CTFPHC AAA screening: identifies men with undetected AAA before rupture. Annual surveillance for AAA 3-4.4 cm; q6 months for 4.5-5.4 cm. Endovascular repair (EVAR) or open repair for ≥5.5 cm. Mortality from ruptured AAA is 80-90%. No benefit shown in women or non-smokers.',2,'recall',['AAA screening','abdominal aortic aneurysm','ultrasound','CTFPHC','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What is universal newborn hearing screening and when is it done?','Otoacoustic emissions (OAE) or automated ABR (AABR) within 24-48 hours of birth; refer for diagnostic audiology if fail — target to identify and treat by 6 months','CASLPA/CPS guidelines: congenital hearing loss occurs in 1-3/1000 live births; early identification (before 6 months) and intervention significantly improves language development. Universal newborn hearing screening (UNHS) is implemented in all Canadian provinces. CI (cochlear implant) eligibility assessed if profound bilateral SNHL.',2,'recall',['newborn hearing screening','UNHS','OAE','hearing loss','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What is the recommendation for vitamin D supplementation in Canadian adults?','Health Canada recommends 600 IU/day for adults 19-70; 800 IU/day for adults >70; Osteoporosis Canada recommends 800-2000 IU/day for adults at risk for osteoporosis — routine serum 25-OH vitamin D testing NOT recommended for the general population','Routine testing is not recommended (CTFPHC) due to imprecise lab tests and lack of evidence that supplementation based on testing improves outcomes. High-risk groups (institutionalized, dark skin, veiled women, malabsorption): supplement without testing. Northern latitude communities have very high rates of deficiency.',2,'recall',['vitamin D supplementation','Health Canada','routine testing','osteoporosis','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What are the Diabetes Canada criteria for screening for type 2 diabetes?','Screen all adults ≥40 years every 3 years with fasting plasma glucose or HbA1c; screen earlier if: BMI ≥25 + ≥1 risk factor (family history, high-risk ethnicity, HTN, dyslipidemia, prior GDM, CVD, prediabetes, polycystic ovarian syndrome)','CANRISK questionnaire can identify high-risk individuals for targeted screening. High-risk ethnicities (South Asian, Black, East Asian, Indigenous, Hispanic, Arab) have higher T2DM prevalence at lower BMI. Early detection allows lifestyle intervention and pharmacotherapy to prevent complications.',2,'recall',['T2DM screening','Diabetes Canada','CANRISK','high-risk populations','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What is the recommended approach to atrial fibrillation screening?','CTFPHC (2020): recommends against routine ECG screening for AF in adults ≥65 without symptoms — pulse assessment by clinician is still standard of practice; wearable devices increasingly identifying paroxysmal AF','CCS AF guidelines: opportunistic screening (pulse assessment, then ECG if irregular) at routine visits is a pragmatic approach. LOOP trial: insertable cardiac monitoring doubled AF detection in stroke survivors. The benefit of AF screening on stroke prevention outcomes is under investigation.',3,'recall',['AF screening','atrial fibrillation','CTFPHC','ECG screening','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What are the hypertension screening recommendations in Canada?','Blood pressure measurement at all appropriate clinical encounters for adults ≥18 years; if elevated, follow Hypertension Canada protocol for confirmation — no specific screening interval recommended as hypertension can develop at any time','Hypertension Canada guidelines: BP should be measured at every primary care visit. Opportunistic screening has been highly effective in Canada. AOBP (automated office BP) is the standard measurement method. Electronic alerts in EMR prompt BP measurement and follow-up.',1,'recall',['hypertension screening','blood pressure','Hypertension Canada','AOBP','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What are the indications for chlamydia and gonorrhea screening in Canada?','Annual screening for: all sexually active women ≤25 years, older women with risk factors (new/multiple partners), all MSM, and individuals with prior STI — PHAC STI guidelines','PHAC recommends screening as part of sexual health history at every clinical encounter for at-risk individuals. Most chlamydia infections are asymptomatic. Universal antenatal chlamydia screening at first prenatal visit. 3-site (pharyngeal, rectal, urogenital) testing for MSM.',2,'recall',['chlamydia screening','gonorrhea screening','STI','PHAC','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What is osteoporosis screening per Osteoporosis Canada guidelines?','DXA for: all women ≥65 and men ≥70; postmenopausal women and men 50-64 with risk factors (prior fragility fracture, steroid use, secondary causes of osteoporosis, FRAX risk ≥10% for major osteoporotic fracture)','Osteoporosis Canada guidelines 2023: FRAX calculation to identify high-risk individuals before DXA. Bone turnover markers and vertebral fracture assessment (VFA) on DXA. Calcium and vitamin D supplementation for all patients at risk. Targeted screening is more cost-effective than universal screening.',2,'recall',['osteoporosis screening','DXA','Osteoporosis Canada','FRAX','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What are the CTFPHC recommendations regarding alcohol and substance use screening?','Brief alcohol screening (AUDIT-C) in primary care; SBIRT (Screening, Brief Intervention, and Referral to Treatment) for adults with harmful/hazardous alcohol or drug use — CTFPHC recommends screening adults for unhealthy alcohol use','CTFPHC 2018 alcohol screening: 5-minute brief intervention after positive AUDIT screen can reduce alcohol consumption by 15-25%. Motivational interviewing approach. Harm reduction approach for other substance use. Opioid risk tool for opioid prescribing.',2,'recall',['alcohol screening','AUDIT','SBIRT','CTFPHC','brief intervention','public health']);
add('ph-screening','What is the recommended schedule for Pap testing vs. HPV primary testing?','Pap test: every 3 years (age 21-69); HPV primary testing: every 5 years (being phased in provincially); HPV+ with negative cytology: re-test in 12 months; HPV+ with abnormal cytology: colposcopy','Ontario and BC are implementing HPV primary testing as standard. HPV16/18 positive on primary test → immediate colposcopy. Other high-risk HPV types positive with abnormal cytology → colposcopy. Advantages of HPV testing: higher sensitivity (90%), longer intervals, earlier detection of CIN.',3,'recall',['HPV primary testing','Pap test','colposcopy','cervical cancer','public health']);

// PUBLIC HEALTH - ph-epidemiology (15)
add('ph-epidemiology','What is the difference between incidence and prevalence?','Incidence: rate of NEW cases in a defined population over a time period; Prevalence: proportion of EXISTING cases (new + old) in a population at a given time — Point prevalence: at specific moment; Period prevalence: over defined time period','Prevalence = Incidence × Duration (of disease). High incidence with short duration (recovery or death) → low prevalence (influenza). Low incidence with long duration (chronic disease) → higher prevalence than incidence (HIV/AIDS). Changing prevalence can reflect changing incidence, mortality, or disease duration.',2,'recall',['incidence','prevalence','epidemiology','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is sensitivity vs. specificity of a screening test?','Sensitivity: proportion of TRUE POSITIVES correctly identified (TP/[TP+FN]); Specificity: proportion of TRUE NEGATIVES correctly identified (TN/[TN+FP]) — high sensitivity = few false negatives; high specificity = few false positives','High sensitivity tests are best for screening (rule out disease — negative test rules disease out: SnNOUT). High specificity tests are best for confirmation (rule in disease — positive test rules disease in: SpPIN). Cancer screening tests prioritize sensitivity; confirmatory tests prioritize specificity.',2,'recall',['sensitivity','specificity','screening test','epidemiology','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is positive predictive value (PPV) and how does disease prevalence affect it?','PPV = TP/(TP+FP) — probability of having disease given a positive test; NPV = TN/(TN+FN); PPV DECREASES when disease prevalence is low (more false positives relative to true positives)','PPV and NPV are affected by disease prevalence (unlike sensitivity and specificity which are fixed characteristics of the test). Same test in a low-prevalence population will have lower PPV than in a high-prevalence population. Crucial when interpreting screening results in general vs. high-risk populations.',3,'apply',['PPV','NPV','positive predictive value','prevalence','epidemiology','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is relative risk (RR) and how is it interpreted?','RR = Risk in exposed / Risk in unexposed; RR=1: no association; RR>1: increased risk; RR<1: decreased risk (protective); used for COHORT studies and RCTs','RR is used for prospective studies. In case-control studies, use Odds Ratio (OR) because incidence cannot be calculated. OR approximates RR when disease is rare (<10%). Absolute risk reduction (ARR) = risk in control − risk in treatment; NNT = 1/ARR.',2,'recall',['relative risk','cohort study','RR interpretation','epidemiology','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is the number needed to treat (NNT) and how is it calculated?','NNT = 1 / ARR (absolute risk reduction); ARR = control event rate − treatment event rate — NNT is the number of patients who need to be treated for one patient to benefit','Low NNT = more effective treatment. NNT must always be interpreted with time frame (NNT at 1 year vs. 5 years). NNH (Number Needed to Harm) = 1/ARI (absolute risk increase). Clinicians should understand NNT to discuss treatment benefits meaningfully with patients.',2,'recall',['NNT','number needed to treat','ARR','absolute risk reduction','epidemiology','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is selection bias and provide an example?','Selection bias: systematic error in how study participants are selected, resulting in non-representative sample; Example: Berkson bias (hospitalized patients more likely to have multiple diseases, making two conditions appear associated when they are not in the general population)','Selection bias leads to study results that cannot be generalized. Healthy worker bias: employed workers are healthier than general population, making occupational studies underestimate mortality risk. Volunteer bias: participants who volunteer may have different characteristics than those who decline.',3,'apply',['selection bias','Berkson bias','epidemiology','study design','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is confounding and how can it be controlled?','Confounding: third variable is associated with both the exposure and outcome, causing a spurious or biased association; Control methods: randomization (RCTs), restriction, matching, stratification, multivariable analysis (regression)','Example: alcohol use appears protective against MI — but smokers drink more alcohol. Smoking is a confounder. Residual confounding: occurs when known confounders are not fully adjusted for. Unmeasured confounders are a limitation of observational studies.',3,'apply',['confounding','confounder','epidemiology','bias','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is the attributable risk (AR) and population attributable risk (PAR)?','AR = Incidence in exposed − Incidence in unexposed (risk in exposed attributable to the exposure); PAR = Incidence in total population − Incidence in unexposed (proportion of disease that would be prevented if exposure eliminated from population)','PAR is used in public health to prioritize interventions. If smoking causes 85% of lung cancers (PAR = 85%), eliminating smoking would prevent 85% of lung cancers. PAR depends on both the relative risk and the prevalence of exposure in the population.',3,'apply',['attributable risk','PAR','population attributable risk','smoking','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is a systematic review vs. meta-analysis?','Systematic review: comprehensive, reproducible literature search and synthesis of evidence on a specific question; Meta-analysis: statistical method to pool results from multiple studies to calculate a summary effect size (gives more power and precision)','Levels of evidence: meta-analysis/systematic reviews > RCTs > cohort studies > case-control > case series. GRADE (Grading of Recommendations Assessment, Development and Evaluation) framework used by Canadian guidelines to rate evidence quality and recommendation strength.',2,'recall',['systematic review','meta-analysis','evidence hierarchy','GRADE','epidemiology','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is a randomized controlled trial (RCT) and why is it the gold standard?','RCT: participants randomly assigned to intervention vs. control — randomization eliminates selection bias and balances known and unknown confounders between groups, allowing causal inference','RCT limitations: expensive, time-consuming, ethical constraints, external validity (generalizability). Double-blind RCT (neither participant nor assessor knows allocation) minimizes performance and detection bias. Intention-to-treat analysis preserves randomization benefits. CONSORT checklist for reporting RCTs.',2,'recall',['RCT','randomized controlled trial','study design','internal validity','epidemiology','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is the difference between a type I error and a type II error?','Type I error (alpha error): false positive — rejecting null hypothesis when it is true; probability = p-value (typically <0.05); Type II error (beta error): false negative — failing to reject null hypothesis when it is false; probability = β (1-β = power, typically 80-90%)','Type I error consequences: accepting a treatment that is actually ineffective. Type II error consequences: missing a real treatment effect. Larger sample size reduces both types of errors. Power (1-β) reflects ability to detect a true effect if it exists.',3,'recall',['type I error','type II error','alpha','beta','statistical power','epidemiology','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is the 95% confidence interval and what does it mean if it does not cross 1.0?','95% CI: range of values within which the true population parameter lies with 95% certainty; if 95% CI for RR or OR does NOT include 1.0 → statistically significant at p<0.05','Narrow CI = more precise estimate (larger sample size). Wide CI = less precise (small sample). If CI crosses 1.0 for RR: result is NOT statistically significant. CI is more informative than p-value alone because it provides information about effect size and precision.',2,'recall',['confidence interval','95% CI','statistical significance','RR','epidemiology','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is lead time bias in screening studies?','Lead time bias: screening appears to prolong survival time because it detects disease earlier (advancing the apparent start of disease), but actual lifespan is not extended — survival appears longer without actually being longer','Screening survival studies must use disease-specific mortality rather than 5-year survival to avoid lead time bias. Length bias: screening is more likely to detect slowly-growing cancers (more time to screen) vs. aggressive fast-growing cancers, making screened cohort appear to do better.',3,'apply',['lead time bias','length bias','screening studies','survival bias','epidemiology','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is the basic reproduction number (R0) and its significance in infectious disease?','R0: average number of secondary cases generated by one infectious case in a fully susceptible population; R0 >1 = epidemic can spread; R0 <1 = outbreak dies out; herd immunity threshold = 1 - (1/R0) × 100%','COVID-19 original strain: R0 ~2-3; Omicron: R0 ~8-15; Measles: R0 12-18 (one of highest known). Herd immunity for measles: (1-1/15) × 100% = 93%. Vaccination coverage must exceed herd immunity threshold to prevent outbreaks. R0 changes with interventions (R effective, Rt).',3,'apply',['R0','basic reproduction number','herd immunity','epidemiology','public health']);
add('ph-epidemiology','What is the Cochrane Collaboration and how do Canadian physicians use it?','Cochrane Collaboration: independent network producing systematic reviews and meta-analyses of healthcare interventions; Cochrane Library contains >8000 systematic reviews; used by clinicians to find highest-quality evidence to inform clinical decisions','Canadian clinical practice guidelines frequently cite Cochrane reviews as the primary evidence source. Cochrane reviews use GRADE to rate evidence quality. Limitations of meta-analysis: garbage in, garbage out — pooling poor-quality studies does not improve evidence quality. Publication bias can skew results.',2,'recall',['Cochrane Collaboration','systematic review','evidence-based medicine','GRADE','public health']);

// PUBLIC HEALTH - ph-social-det (10)
add('ph-social-det','What are the social determinants of health (SDOH) and how do they affect health outcomes?','SDOH: non-medical factors influencing health — income and wealth, education, employment, housing, food security, social support, early childhood development, Indigenous status, disability, race/racism, gender — account for 30-55% of health outcomes','WHO Commission on SDOH (2008): unfair distribution of SDOH is responsible for most health inequities globally. In Canada: individuals in lowest income quintile have 7-10 year lower life expectancy than highest quintile. PHAC uses SDOH framework for population health policy.',2,'recall',['social determinants of health','SDOH','health inequity','public health']);
add('ph-social-det','What is the health gradient and what does it demonstrate?','Health gradient: continuous dose-response relationship between socioeconomic status and health outcomes — those at the top are healthier than those just below them, all the way down the social ladder (not just poor vs. non-poor)','Whitehall studies (UK civil servants): demonstrated that even within a working, employed population, there is a continuous gradient of health — those with higher job grade had better health. Gradient reflects differential exposure to SDOH, not just absolute poverty.',2,'recall',['health gradient','socioeconomic status','Whitehall study','health inequity','public health']);
add('ph-social-det','What are the health disparities faced by Indigenous Peoples in Canada?','Higher rates of: T2DM (3-5x), TB (10x), suicide (3x for First Nations adults, up to 10x for Inuit youth), infant mortality (2x), poverty, food insecurity, substance use, mental health issues; shorter life expectancy by 10-15 years','PHAC and Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC): health disparities in Indigenous peoples are the result of colonization, residential schools, systemic racism, and ongoing socioeconomic inequities. Cultural safety and Indigenous-led health services are essential. Physicians should be aware of trauma-informed care.',3,'apply',['Indigenous health','health disparities','colonization','social determinants','public health']);
add('ph-social-det','What is structural racism and how does it affect healthcare?','Structural racism: laws, policies, and institutional practices that disadvantage racialized groups — manifests in healthcare as unequal access, implicit bias, delayed diagnoses, and treatment disparities for Black, Indigenous, and other racialized peoples in Canada','CMAJ (Canadian Medical Association Journal) and CMA have acknowledged systemic racism in Canadian healthcare. Examples: anti-Indigenous racism in emergency rooms (Joyce Echaquan), racial disparities in pain management, lower cancer screening rates. Antiracism training and cultural humility are required competencies.',3,'apply',['structural racism','healthcare disparities','racialized populations','cultural safety','public health']);
add('ph-social-det','What is food insecurity and what are its health consequences?','Food insecurity: inadequate or uncertain access to enough food due to lack of resources; associated with: T2DM, cardiovascular disease, poor mental health, higher mortality — affects ~12% of Canadian households','PHAC statistics: food insecurity is highest among Indigenous peoples (28%), racialized communities, single-parent households, low-income families. Adequate income (basic income) is more effective than food banks for addressing food insecurity. Clinical screening: Hunger Vital Sign (2-question tool).',2,'recall',['food insecurity','Hunger Vital Sign','social determinants','public health']);
add('ph-social-det','What is housing insecurity and homelessness, and how does it affect health?','Housing insecurity/homelessness: associated with increased rates of infectious disease (TB, HIV, hepatitis C), mental illness, substance use, injury, trauma, and 3-10x higher mortality than housed individuals of same age','PHAC: ~235,000 Canadians experience homelessness annually. Housing First approach (Pathways to Housing): provide stable housing without prerequisites — reduces hospitalizations and emergency visits by 50%. Clinical: inquire about housing at every visit; connect with social services.',3,'apply',['homelessness','housing insecurity','Housing First','public health']);
add('ph-social-det','What is the adverse childhood experiences (ACEs) framework?','ACEs: traumatic childhood experiences (abuse, neglect, household dysfunction) associated with dose-response increases in adult health risks (CVD, cancer, substance use, mental illness, premature death) — 4+ ACEs triples risk of many adverse outcomes','CDC ACE study: ACEs are extremely common (64% of Americans have ≥1; 12% have ≥4) and have lifelong health consequences via toxic stress mechanisms (HPA axis dysregulation, inflammation). Trauma-informed care is a core competency for Canadian physicians. Screening: ACE questionnaire.',3,'recall',['ACEs','adverse childhood experiences','toxic stress','trauma-informed care','public health']);
add('ph-social-det','What is health literacy and why is it important in clinical care?','Health literacy: ability to obtain, process, and understand health information to make informed decisions; low health literacy associated with poor adherence, more ED visits, higher mortality — affects ~55% of Canadians','Canadian Institute for Health Information: health literacy varies across populations (lower in elderly, immigrants, low education). Strategies: plain language, teach-back method, pictorial instructions, avoiding medical jargon. All educational materials should be at Grade 6 reading level or lower.',2,'recall',['health literacy','patient education','plain language','teach-back','public health']);
add('ph-social-det','What is the Ottawa Charter for Health Promotion?','Ottawa Charter (1986): first international conference on health promotion; 5 action areas: Build Healthy Public Policy, Create Supportive Environments, Strengthen Community Action, Develop Personal Skills, Reorient Health Services; prerequisites for health: peace, shelter, education, food, income, equity','The Ottawa Charter shifted focus from individual behavior to social determinants. Health promotion: enabling people to increase control over and improve their health. Social gradient of health recognized. Canadian contribution: Marc Lalonde report (1974) — first national health framework recognizing social determinants.',2,'recall',['Ottawa Charter','health promotion','Lalonde report','social determinants','public health']);
add('ph-social-det','What are the principles of cultural humility and cultural safety in Canadian healthcare?','Cultural humility: lifelong commitment to self-reflection, learning from others, power imbalances in healthcare; Cultural safety: environment where patients feel safe to express cultural identity without judgment; goes beyond cultural competence (mastering facts about cultures) to systemic power analysis','College of Family Physicians of Canada and Medical Council of Canada: cultural safety and humility are core competencies. Requires recognizing and addressing systemic racism, colonialism, and power differentials. Indigenous patients: duty to provide culturally safe care. Resource: Indigenous Cultural Safety Training.',3,'recall',['cultural safety','cultural humility','Indigenous health','systemic racism','public health']);

// ETHICS - ethics-consent (15)
add('ethics-consent','A 78-year-old with early dementia wants to refuse amputation for a gangrenous foot. How do you assess capacity for this decision?','Capacity assessment: patient must demonstrate UNDERSTANDING the information, APPRECIATION of how it applies to their situation, REASONING through the options, and COMMUNICATION of a choice (4 criteria — Aid MacIAT/ACE tests)','Capacity is decision-specific and may fluctuate. CMPA guidelines: capacity must be assessed for each decision. Presume capacity unless evidence suggests otherwise. Cognitive tests (MMSE, MoCA) do not replace formal capacity assessment. If lacking capacity: substitute decision-maker uses prior wishes or best interests.',5,'analyze',['capacity assessment','informed consent','decision-making capacity','dementia','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','What are the elements of informed consent?','Patient must be: competent (has capacity), informed (understands diagnosis, proposed treatment, alternatives, risks, benefits, consequences of refusing), and voluntary (no coercion) — documented in medical record','CMPA guidelines: informed consent is a process, not just a signature. Tarasoff standard: disclose material risks (those a reasonable person would want to know, plus specific risks this patient would want to know). Risk should be disclosed in terms of probability AND severity.',3,'recall',['informed consent','capacity','voluntariness','CMPA','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','Who acts as substitute decision-maker (SDM) when a patient lacks capacity in Ontario?','SDM hierarchy in Ontario (Health Care Consent Act): 1) Appointed attorney for personal care (POA), 2) Spouse/partner, 3) Parent/child (18+), 4) Sibling, 5) Any other relative, 6) Public Guardian and Trustee','SDM hierarchy varies by province. SDM must use incapable person\'s prior expressed wishes and values (if known), or in their best interests if wishes unknown. SDM cannot authorize medical assistance in dying (MAID). Consent and Capacity Board (CCB) in Ontario adjudicates disputes.',3,'apply',['substitute decision-maker','SDM','Ontario','capacity','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','What is the difference between capacity and competence?','Capacity: clinical assessment by a healthcare provider of the patient\'s ability to make a specific healthcare decision; Competence: legal determination by a court that a person is or is not capable of managing their affairs','In practice, "capacity" is used in clinical settings for healthcare decisions. "Competence" is the legal term for broader decision-making ability (finances, legal decisions). Physicians assess capacity; courts determine competence. All adults are presumed capable unless assessed otherwise.',2,'recall',['capacity vs competence','legal capacity','clinical assessment','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','A competent patient refuses a blood transfusion as a Jehovah\'s Witness. What is the physician\'s obligation?','Respect the patient\'s autonomy and informed refusal — do not administer blood products; document the refusal; offer alternative treatments (cell salvage, erythropoietin, volume expanders); explore patient\'s values and wishes in advance','CMPA guidelines: a competent adult has the right to refuse ANY medical treatment, even life-saving treatment. Physician must ensure the refusal is informed (patient understands consequences). Document thoroughly. Ethics consultation helpful. Court applications for children of Jehovah\'s Witnesses are different.',4,'analyze',['Jehovah\'s Witness','refusal of treatment','autonomy','informed refusal','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','What is an advance directive and what types exist in Canada?','Advance directive: written instructions for future healthcare when patient lacks capacity; Types: (1) Living will (instructional — specific wishes), (2) Power of Attorney for Personal Care (POAPC — designates a substitute decision-maker)','Provincial legislation governs advance directives. Living wills are instructional and tell SDMs what the patient would want. POAPC is the most practical form. Healthcare teams must honor valid advance directives. All patients should be encouraged to complete advance directives while capable.',2,'recall',['advance directive','living will','POA','advance care planning','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','How should informed consent be obtained for a research study involving patients?','Research ethics board (REB) approval required; written informed consent with full disclosure of: purpose, methods, risks and benefits, confidentiality, voluntary participation, right to withdraw without consequences; research consent is separate from clinical consent','TCPS2 (Tri-Council Policy Statement) governs research involving humans in Canada. Vulnerable populations (cognitively impaired, prisoners, children) require additional protections. Waiver of consent allowed if research involves minimal risk and consent is impractical.',3,'apply',['research consent','REB','TCPS2','research ethics','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','A 15-year-old presents alone requesting contraception. Can consent be obtained without parental involvement?','Yes — mature minor doctrine: adolescents who can demonstrate capacity can consent to healthcare independently; most provinces recognize the mature minor doctrine for healthcare decisions','Provincial legislation varies. In most Canadian provinces, adolescents can consent to their own healthcare (including contraception, STI testing/treatment, mental health) if they demonstrate capacity. Physician assesses capacity — explain information about contraception, confirm understanding, check for coercion.',3,'apply',['mature minor','adolescent consent','capacity','contraception','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','What is therapeutic privilege and is it ethically defensible?','Therapeutic privilege: withholding information from patients to prevent psychological harm — NOT generally accepted in Canada; physicians cannot withhold information they believe the patient would want','CMPA guidelines strongly discourage therapeutic privilege. Exceptions: when disclosure would cause direct, immediate harm (rare). Physicians may choose timing and framing of difficult information, but cannot withhold material information. Cultural differences in information preferences should be explored and respected.',3,'recall',['therapeutic privilege','informed consent','information disclosure','CMPA','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','What is the process for obtaining consent for an incapable person from their SDM?','SDM must use: (1) prior capable wishes if known (including advance directives); (2) if no prior wishes: known values and beliefs of the incapable person; (3) if unknown: best interests (considering well-being, consistent values, and avoid unnecessary suffering)','Ontario Health Care Consent Act: SDM is bound by these principles in hierarchical order. Best interests is the last resort. SDM cannot impose their own values on the incapable person. Consent and Capacity Board can review SDM decisions that appear contrary to the patient\'s best interests.',4,'apply',['SDM','substitute decision-maker','best interests','advance care planning','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','A patient with schizophrenia is refusing hospitalization. He has paranoid delusions that are causing him to not eat. What are the options?','If patient lacks capacity: seek consent from SDM or apply for Community Treatment Order (CTO) or involuntary admission under provincial Mental Health Act; if capacity retained: respect refusal, maximize community support','Mental health capacity is assessed using the same criteria. Psychotic patients may retain capacity for healthcare decisions even with active psychosis if they can understand and appreciate. Involuntary hospitalization requires: mental disorder + serious bodily harm to self or others + hospitalization needed. Form 1 in Ontario.',4,'analyze',['mental capacity','psychosis','involuntary admission','Mental Health Act','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','What is a do-not-resuscitate (DNR) order and how should it be established?','DNR order: documents patient\'s wish to not receive CPR in the event of cardiac/respiratory arrest — should be discussed proactively with all patients with serious illness; NOT a general "do not treat" order','CMPA guidelines: DNR orders require informed consent discussion (goals of care conversation), documented in chart, and regularly reviewed. DNR order does not mean "comfort care only" — all other treatments continue unless separately addressed. POLST/MOST forms document broader goals of care.',4,'apply',['DNR','do not resuscitate','goals of care','POLST','MOST','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','What are the rights of patients who are involuntarily admitted under a Mental Health Act?','Rights: (1) right to be told reasons for admission, (2) right to retain legal counsel, (3) right to have admission reviewed (mental health tribunal/board), (4) right to refuse treatment even when involuntary (capacity still governs treatment consent), (5) right to have substitute decision-maker for treatment decisions','Being involuntarily hospitalized does NOT remove a patient\'s right to refuse treatment. Separate capacity assessment and SDM involvement required for treatment decisions. Rights adviser visits involuntary patients in Ontario to explain rights. Review board/tribunal can discharge if admission criteria not met.',4,'apply',['involuntary admission','patient rights','Mental Health Act','capacity','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','What is the Capable Consent to Treatment and how does it differ from MAID consent?','Regular treatment consent: capable patient, informed of options, voluntary decision; MAID consent: additional safeguards — two assessments by independent practitioners, 10-day reflection period (waivable for imminent loss of capacity), written request, witness requirements','MAID (Medical Assistance in Dying): Bill C-7 expanded eligibility beyond end of life. Additional protections: final consent can be waived in advance for loss of capacity if suffering from serious neurocognitive illness. Bill C-7 consultation period for mental illness as sole condition.',4,'apply',['MAID consent','medical assistance in dying','consent safeguards','Bill C-7','ethics']);
add('ethics-consent','What is the duty of a physician when a capable patient consents to a procedure but then becomes uncapable during the procedure?','If patient gave prior capable consent and becomes incapable during the procedure (e.g., anesthesia), physician can continue the procedure the patient consented to — do NOT need to stop and get SDM consent','This applies to the specific procedure consented to. Any expansion of the procedure beyond what was consented to requires SDM consent unless it is an emergency. If the patient had an advance directive addressing this situation, it applies. CMPA guidance on intraoperative consent issues.',3,'apply',['intraoperative consent','treatment continuation','capacity','anesthesia','ethics']);

// ETHICS - ethics-end-of-life (10)
add('ethics-end-of-life','What is Medical Assistance in Dying (MAID) in Canada and who is eligible?','MAID (Bill C-14, 2016; amended Bill C-7, 2021): adult with serious and incurable illness, disease, or disability; advanced state of irreversible decline; experiencing grievous and intolerable suffering (physical or psychological); grievous and irremediable condition — natural death need not be reasonably foreseeable','MAID in Canada is the most comprehensive in the world. Exclusions: mental illness as sole underlying condition (planned eligibility 2024); non-therapeutic permanent disabilities; minors. Two assessors + 10-day reflection period. Optional for physicians (conscience exemption must ensure patient access to another provider).',3,'recall',['MAID','medical assistance in dying','Bill C-7','Canada','ethics']);
add('ethics-end-of-life','What is the difference between palliative sedation, palliative care, and MAID?','Palliative sedation: sedation to unconsciousness to relieve refractory suffering at end of life (NOT intended to hasten death); Palliative care: comfort-focused care that may be concurrent with disease-directed treatment; MAID: physician actively ending patient\'s life at their explicit request','Double effect principle justifies palliative sedation and high-dose opioids for symptom control if the primary intent is comfort, not death acceleration. MAID requires explicit, capable, repeated request and meets legal eligibility criteria. Palliative sedation does not require MAID eligibility criteria.',4,'analyze',['palliative sedation','MAID','double effect principle','palliative care','ethics']);
add('ethics-end-of-life','What are the principles of good palliative care?','Pain and symptom management, comfort-focused goals of care, psychosocial-spiritual support, advance care planning, family support (including bereavement), avoiding unnecessary interventions, patient-centered care','Canadian Hospice Palliative Care Association (CHPCA): palliative care should begin at diagnosis for serious illness (concurrent with disease-directed treatment), not just at end of life. Early palliative care referral improves quality of life and may extend survival (NEJM Temel study).',2,'recall',['palliative care','end of life','CHPCA','advance care planning','ethics']);
add('ethics-end-of-life','A patient with terminal cancer has severe pain despite high-dose oral opioids. What options exist?','Rotate opioids (incomplete cross-tolerance may improve analgesia), increase dose, add adjuvant analgesics (steroids, anticonvulsants, TCAs for neuropathic pain), consider interventional pain management (nerve blocks, epidural), palliative sedation for refractory suffering','CHPCA guidelines: opioids are the cornerstone of cancer pain management. WHO analgesic ladder: non-opioids → weak opioids → strong opioids ± adjuvants. Opioids do not hasten death when used appropriately. Opiophobia and undertreatment of cancer pain are significant problems.',4,'apply',['cancer pain','opioid rotation','palliative care','end of life','ethics']);
add('ethics-end-of-life','What are the ethical principles involved in withdrawing life-sustaining treatment?','Withdrawing life-sustaining treatment (mechanical ventilation, dialysis, artificial nutrition) when: patient or SDM requests withdrawal, goals of care have shifted, or treatment is no longer in patient\'s best interests — ethically equivalent to not starting treatment (withholding)','Canadian ethicists and the courts agree: there is no ethical or legal difference between withholding and withdrawing life support. Once started, treatment can be withdrawn. SDM must guide decisions for incapable patients using prior wishes or best interests. Palliative sedation may accompany ventilator withdrawal.',4,'analyze',['withdrawal of life support','withholding treatment','SDM','palliative care','ethics']);
add('ethics-end-of-life','What is prognostication and why is it important in end-of-life care?','Prognostication: estimating likely disease course and life expectancy; important for: goals of care discussions, advance care planning, appropriate palliative care referral, avoiding unwanted aggressive interventions, and enabling final preparations','Clinicians systematically over-estimate prognosis in cancer and serious illness. Validated tools: PPS (Palliative Performance Scale), Surprise Question ("Would I be surprised if this patient died in the next year?"), PaP score. Honest communication improves decision-making and reduces aggressive end-of-life care.',3,'apply',['prognostication','palliative care','goals of care','PPS','ethics']);
add('ethics-end-of-life','What are the signs of imminent death in the dying patient?','Signs of imminent death (hours to days): Cheyne-Stokes or irregular breathing, mottled skin (livedo reticularis), cooling of extremities, Kussmaul breathing, gurgling respirations (death rattle), decreased consciousness, inability to swallow','CHPCA End-of-Life Care Recommendations: family education about signs of dying reduces distress. Glycopyrrolate reduces death rattle (secretion management). Comfort measures: position for comfort, moist mouth care, discontinue vitals and monitoring, restrict unnecessary medications, reposition q4h.',2,'recall',['imminent death','dying process','palliative care','family support','ethics']);
add('ethics-end-of-life','What is the role of truth-telling in communicating a serious diagnosis?','Physicians are ethically and legally obligated to be truthful with patients who have capacity — withholding a diagnosis violates patient autonomy; frame truth compassionately, give information in digestible amounts, ensure follow-up support','CMPA guidelines: cultural practices of withholding diagnosis from patients (common in some cultures) cannot override patient\'s right to know their diagnosis. However, physician can explore patient\'s information preferences ("how much detail would you like me to share?"). Third-party requests to withhold information must be addressed.',3,'apply',['truth-telling','serious diagnosis','communication','autonomy','ethics']);
add('ethics-end-of-life','What are the obligations when a patient requests MAID but you have a conscientious objection?','Physician must provide an effective referral to a provider who will provide MAID — refusing to provide referral violates the patient\'s Charter right to access a legal medical service','CMA and provincial colleges: conscientious objection is a protected right but does not extend to obstructing patient access. Physician must provide all relevant clinical information to the patient and facilitate timely transfer of care. System must not allow conscientious objection to create barriers to access.',4,'apply',['conscientious objection','MAID','effective referral','CMA','ethics']);
add('ethics-end-of-life','What is a goals of care conversation and what does it involve?','Goals of care: exploring patient values, understanding prognosis, identifying treatment goals (cure, extend life, maintain function, quality of life, comfort) and matching treatment plan to goals — using SPIKES protocol for difficult conversations','SPIKES protocol: Setting up, Perception (what does patient know/want to know), Invitation (how much detail), Knowledge (giving information), Empathy and Exploration, Strategy and Summary. CHPCA recommends goals of care conversations for all patients with serious illness.',3,'apply',['goals of care','SPIKES protocol','advance care planning','palliative care','ethics']);

// ETHICS - ethics-confidentiality (10)
add('ethics-confidentiality','When is a physician permitted to break patient confidentiality?','Mandatory reporting: communicable diseases (public health legislation), child abuse/neglect, gunshot wounds; Discretionary: imminent danger to identifiable third party (Tarasoff duty to protect), fitness to drive impairment, child protection','CMPA guidelines: confidentiality is a cornerstone of the physician-patient relationship. Exceptions require a higher ethical duty. Physicians in Canada do not have a "duty to warn" in the same way as the US Tarasoff ruling — but provinces have various discretionary and mandatory reporting laws.',3,'apply',['confidentiality','mandatory reporting','Tarasoff','duty to warn','ethics']);
add('ethics-confidentiality','What are the mandatory reporting obligations for physicians in Ontario regarding child abuse?','ALL healthcare professionals (and others) who reasonably suspect a child under 16 (Ontario — 18 in some provinces) is being abused or neglected MUST report to the Children\'s Aid Society (CAS) — duty is personal and cannot be delegated','CMPA: reporting child abuse is a positive legal duty — failure to report is an offense under the Child, Youth and Family Services Act. Report any reasonable suspicion — physicians do not need certainty. Report even if child or parents ask you not to. CAS investigates; physician\'s role is to report, not investigate.',3,'apply',['mandatory reporting','child abuse','CAS','Ontario','ethics']);
add('ethics-confidentiality','A patient tells you they plan to seriously harm their ex-partner. What are your obligations?','Duty to protect: warn the potential victim, notify police, consider involuntary hospitalization — balance confidentiality against duty to protect identifiable third party from serious bodily harm','Canadian law (Tsilhqot\'in v. BC, provincial legislation): no universal Tarasoff-style duty to warn in all provinces, but most colleges and CMPA guidelines support discretionary disclosure to protect identifiable third party from serious, imminent harm. Exhaust other options first (hospitalization, persuasion to seek help).',4,'analyze',['duty to warn','confidentiality','Tarasoff','third party protection','ethics']);
add('ethics-confidentiality','What is the physician\'s obligation regarding reporting unfit drivers?','Report to Ministry of Transportation (mandatory in Ontario and most provinces) when patient has a medical condition affecting safe driving ability that the patient refuses to voluntarily stop driving or report themselves','Highway Traffic Act (Ontario): physician has mandatory duty to report patients with medical conditions affecting fitness to drive if patient refuses to self-report. Protected from liability for reporting in good faith. Advise patient of the reporting obligation first. Vision, dementia, epilepsy, cardiac conditions are common.',3,'apply',['driving fitness','mandatory reporting','MTO','medical condition','ethics']);
add('ethics-confidentiality','What information can be disclosed to insurance companies or employers?','Only information the patient has explicitly authorized in writing — insurance companies and employers are NOT entitled to information without patient consent; physician should provide only information relevant to the request','CMPA: informed consent for disclosure to third parties is required. Patient should understand what information will be released and to whom. Physicians should exercise professional judgment about what is clinically relevant. IME (Independent Medical Examination) reports have different confidentiality rules.',2,'recall',['third party disclosure','insurance','employer','patient consent','ethics']);
add('ethics-confidentiality','What are a patient\'s rights regarding access to their own medical records?','Patients have the right to access their own medical records in most circumstances — physician may withhold information if disclosure would cause direct harm (PHIPA Ontario); 30-day response time required','PHIPA (Personal Health Information Protection Act) Ontario: patient right to access records within 30 days. Physician may refuse access if: disclosure would result in risk of serious bodily harm, information is about third parties. Patient can request amendment of their record.',2,'recall',['medical records access','PHIPA','patient rights','confidentiality','ethics']);
add('ethics-confidentiality','What is the duty of a physician when they learn a colleague is impaired?','Report to the relevant regulatory college (CPSO in Ontario) or hospital department chief; Canadian provincial colleges have policies on physician impairment — duty to report and protect patients','CMPA and CPSO: physician health programs (e.g., PHP in Ontario) exist to support impaired physicians. Colleagues should encourage voluntary participation. If patient safety is at risk, mandatory reporting is required. CMA Code of Ethics: duty to protect public from impaired colleagues.',3,'apply',['impaired physician','mandatory reporting','CPSO','physician health','ethics']);
add('ethics-confidentiality','A patient with HIV refuses to disclose their status to their sexual partner. What should the physician do?','Counsel patient about risk to partners; if patient refuses disclosure and continues to pose risk: notify public health (mandatory for HIV under public health legislation in most provinces); public health officer can then notify partner','Most Canadian provinces: HIV is notifiable to public health. Public health officer (not physician directly) notifies contacts if patient refuses. Physician should exhaust persuasion before notifying. Balancing confidentiality and public health protection is a legal and ethical obligation.',4,'analyze',['HIV disclosure','partner notification','public health reporting','confidentiality','ethics']);
add('ethics-confidentiality','What is the therapeutic exception to informed consent?','Therapeutic exception: information can be withheld if it would cause direct psychological harm sufficient to impair rational decision-making capacity — extremely narrow exception, NOT to be used to withhold information to avoid "upsetting" patient','CMPA: therapeutic exception is controversial and rarely applicable. Physician must document justification clearly. Cultural requests to withhold information must be balanced against patient autonomy. Pre-empting distress by providing information thoughtfully is preferable to invoking therapeutic exception.',3,'recall',['therapeutic exception','informed consent','withholding information','CMPA','ethics']);
add('ethics-confidentiality','What are the obligations when a patient discloses domestic violence?','Screen for safety, offer resources (shelters, legal aid, counseling), document in chart with patient\'s consent, report to police ONLY if patient consents (except for mandatory reporting of child abuse if children at risk) — do NOT report without consent in adult DV','CMPA and CMA: mandatory reporting of domestic violence against competent adults does NOT exist in Canada (unlike child abuse). Respecting patient autonomy means not reporting without consent — could worsen safety if abuser is notified. Safety planning, community resources, and follow-up are the physician\'s role.',4,'analyze',['domestic violence','reporting obligations','safety planning','patient consent','ethics']);

// FAMILY MEDICINE - fm-preventive (15)
add('fm-preventive','What immunizations are routinely recommended for adults in Canada?','Influenza (annual), Td/Tdap (every 10 years), Pneumococcal (PCV20 once, or PCV15+PPSV23 sequence for age ≥65 or high risk), Shingles (Shingrix x2, age ≥50), COVID-19 (updated as recommended), Hepatitis A/B (if not immune), RSV (≥60 years)','NACI adult immunization schedule is updated annually. Shingrix (recombinant zoster vaccine) is >90% effective at preventing shingles — recommended for all adults ≥50 regardless of prior chickenpox. HPV vaccine recommended for adults up to age 45 who were not previously vaccinated.',2,'recall',['adult immunization','influenza','Tdap','Shingrix','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What is the recommended approach to cardiovascular risk reduction in primary prevention?','10-year Framingham Risk Score or SCORE2; low-risk: lifestyle modification; intermediate risk (10-20%): shared decision-making for statin; high risk (>20%) or established CVD: statin + lifestyle + BP control + aspirin (secondary prevention only)','CCS Dyslipidemia Guidelines: statins reduce CVD events proportional to LDL reduction (~22% reduction per 1 mmol/L LDL drop). CTFPHC recommends aspirin only for secondary prevention — primary prevention aspirin increases bleeding risk without clear net benefit in low-risk patients.',3,'apply',['CVD prevention','Framingham','statin','primary prevention','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What lifestyle counseling should be offered to all adult patients?','Smoking cessation (most important), physical activity (150 min/week moderate intensity), healthy diet (DASH or Mediterranean), weight management (BMI 18.5-24.9), alcohol reduction (≤10 drinks/week), stress management, sleep hygiene','CTFPHC and CMA: brief counseling for lifestyle modification at every primary care visit. 5 A\'s model (Ask, Advise, Assess, Assist, Arrange) for smoking cessation. Canadian 24-Hour Movement Guidelines: 150 min moderate-vigorous activity + 2 muscle-strengthening days per week.',2,'recall',['lifestyle counseling','smoking cessation','physical activity','diet','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What is the recommended approach to prostate cancer screening in primary care?','Individualized decision-making for men 50-70 with PSA: discuss benefits (mortality reduction ~20-30%) and harms (overdiagnosis, overtreatment, impotence, incontinence); CTFPHC recommends against routine PSA screening','CTFPHC recommends against routine PSA screening due to net harm from overdiagnosis and overtreatment. However, patient autonomy allows informed men to choose PSA testing after a thorough discussion. High-risk men (Black men, family history of prostate cancer): earlier screening discussion.',3,'apply',['prostate cancer screening','PSA','CTFPHC','shared decision-making','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','When should low-dose aspirin be prescribed for primary prevention?','Low-dose aspirin (81 mg/day) is NOT recommended for primary prevention of CVD in adults without established CVD due to increased bleeding risk (GI bleeding, hemorrhagic stroke) outweighing modest CV benefit','CTFPHC 2022 guideline: recommends against initiating aspirin for primary prevention in adults ≥60 years. For 40-59 years with ≥10% 10-year CVD risk: individualized decision (marginal net benefit). Aspirin continues for secondary prevention (after MI, stroke, established CAD).',3,'recall',['aspirin primary prevention','CTFPHC','cardiovascular','bleeding risk','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What is the Canadian approach to depression screening in primary care?','PHQ-2 (2-question screen) at every appropriate visit; if positive, full PHQ-9; CTFPHC: screening adults ≥18 for depression if there is adequate care available to treat and follow up detected cases','Canadian population health: depression affects 11% of Canadians annually. Collaborative care models (primary care + mental health specialist) improve outcomes. CTFPHC recommends against screening if treatment is not available. Brief intervention (counseling or antidepressants) in primary care is effective.',2,'recall',['depression screening','PHQ-2','PHQ-9','CTFPHC','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What is the evidence for health screening in older adults and when should screening be stopped?','Screening should only be done when patient would benefit from early detection and treatment; general guideline: stop screening when life expectancy <10 years or when patient would not undergo further investigation or treatment','CTFPHC: de-prescribing of screening in frail elderly is appropriate. Mammogram in a 90-year-old with dementia and life expectancy 2 years: no benefit. Shared decision-making about discontinuing preventive interventions as functional status declines.',3,'apply',['screening older adults','de-prescribing','life expectancy','frailty','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What is the Canadian recommendation for universal HIV testing?','CTFPHC: HIV testing recommended for all adults 15-65 as part of routine care; universal testing in high-prevalence settings (correctional facilities, addiction programs); annual testing for high-risk individuals','PHAC: 1 in 4 Canadians with HIV is unaware of their status. Universal testing in primary care increases detection. CTFPHC 2019 recommendation: opt-out testing for all adults at least once. HIV testing in pregnancy: universal at first prenatal visit.',2,'recall',['HIV testing','universal screening','CTFPHC','primary care','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What are the recommended blood pressure targets and monitoring intervals in primary prevention?','All adults: measure at every visit; if normal (<130/80): every 2-3 years; if elevated (130-139/80-89): confirm with AOBP or home BP, lifestyle counseling; if ≥140/90: initiate treatment per Hypertension Canada guidelines','Hypertension Canada recommends AOBP as the standard office measurement. BP ≥130/80 with high CVD risk: consider treatment. Hypertension Canada: 90% of Canadians will develop hypertension if they live into their 80s — lifestyle modification throughout life is key.',1,'recall',['blood pressure monitoring','hypertension prevention','lifestyle','Hypertension Canada','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What is the recommended approach to fall prevention in older adults?','Multifactorial assessment + individualized intervention: exercise (balance and strength), medication review (polypharmacy, benzodiazepines, antihypertensives), vision correction, home hazard reduction, foot care, Vitamin D supplementation','CTFPHC: exercise programs (tai chi, strength/balance training) have the strongest evidence for fall prevention. Vitamin D 800 IU/day reduces falls in deficient elderly. Annual medication review — fall-risk medications (opioids, benzodiazepines, antipsychotics, antihypertensives) should be minimized.',3,'apply',['fall prevention','older adults','polypharmacy','exercise','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What is healthy aging and the key preventive measures in adults over 65?','Healthy aging: maintaining functional ability; interventions: exercise (150 min/week), protein intake ≥1.2 g/kg, fall prevention, cognitive engagement, social connection, managing chronic diseases, advance care planning, vaccinations (influenza, pneumococcal, shingles, COVID-19)','CPS and CTFPHC healthy aging guidelines: frailty screening (Clinical Frailty Scale) guides approach to treatment. Comprehensive geriatric assessment (CGA) optimizes care for frail elderly. Medication review (Beers Criteria or STOPP/START) essential to identify inappropriate medications.',2,'recall',['healthy aging','older adults','frailty','CGA','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What is the CAGE questionnaire and when should it be used in primary care?','CAGE: Cut down, Annoyed, Guilty, Eye-opener — 2+ positive = probable alcohol use disorder; use in primary care for alcohol screening in all adult patients at every visit or annual health exam','CAMH recommends integrating alcohol and substance use screening into routine primary care. CAGE has lower sensitivity for hazardous drinking (does not detect it); AUDIT-C preferred for detecting problem drinking spectrum. SBIRT approach: brief intervention after positive screen.',1,'recall',['CAGE questionnaire','alcohol screening','primary care','SBIRT','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What are the benefits of physical activity for primary prevention?','Physical activity reduces: CVD risk (35%), T2DM risk (50%), colon cancer (25-30%), breast cancer (20-30%), depression and anxiety, cognitive decline, falls in elderly, all-cause mortality (30%)','CSEP (Canadian Society for Exercise Physiology) Canadian 24-Hour Movement Guidelines: 150 min moderate-vigorous activity + 2 strength training sessions per week for adults. Even 15 min/day of brisk walking reduces mortality by 14%. "Every step counts" — sedentary time should be minimized.',2,'recall',['physical activity','primary prevention','CVD','diabetes prevention','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What is comprehensive geriatric assessment (CGA) and when should it be used?','CGA: multidimensional interdisciplinary assessment of functional status (ADLs/IADLs), cognition, mood, social support, medications, nutrition, gait/balance, sensory impairment — indicated for complex elderly patients, before major surgery, on hospital admission','CGA by geriatrician reduces iatrogenic harm, inappropriate medication, functional decline. STOPP (Screening Tool of Older Persons\' Prescriptions) and START criteria guide medication review. Frailty assessment using Clinical Frailty Scale (1-9) guides goals of care and treatment intensity.',3,'apply',['CGA','comprehensive geriatric assessment','frailty','STOPP START','family medicine']);
add('fm-preventive','What is the approach to smoking cessation counseling in primary care?','5 A\'s: Ask (tobacco use status), Advise (clear advice to quit), Assess (readiness to quit), Assist (prescribe cessation aid — varenicline first-line), Arrange (follow-up within 1 week); 3B\'s alternative: Brief, Simple, and Directive','CTFPHC: physicians should screen for tobacco use at every visit. Brief advice (30 seconds) increases quit rates. Combined pharmacotherapy + behavioral support doubles success rates. Varenicline 12 weeks of treatment doubles long-term abstinence vs. NRT. Nicotine replacement therapy is available OTC.',2,'recall',['smoking cessation','5 A\'s','varenicline','NRT','family medicine']);

